[2026-03-23]
CATEGORY: OTHER
SERVICE: knowledge
TASK: Architecture decision — retrieval mechanism for knowledge service
SYMPTOM: Not a bug — a strategic decision recorded for future reference.
         Graphiti + Neo4j was the chosen retrieval architecture after the Sprint 1 spike.
         Before Sprint 2 implementation began, the approach was re-evaluated and replaced.
ROOT_CAUSE: The corpus (~100K tokens across 7 documents) is small enough to fit in a single
            Vertex AI context cache. Full-context retrieval over the whole corpus is strictly
            superior to RAG at this scale: no chunking errors, no missed cross-document
            relationships, no embedding drift, no graph extraction failures (as observed
            in Sprint 1 with Graphiti fixating on staff names instead of operational facts).
            RAG adds complexity (chunking, embedding, graph, retrieval tuning) without
            providing any benefit when the corpus fits in one cache.
            At 500 queries/day max and ~100K tokens, cost is acceptable.
PREVENTED_BY: A scale-vs-complexity decision framework in CLAUDE.md would surface this
              earlier: "If corpus fits in context cache, prefer full-context over RAG.
              Re-evaluate only when corpus exceeds cache limits or cost becomes prohibitive."
SOLUTION: Replace Graphiti + Neo4j + OpenAI with Vertex AI Context Caching + Gemini 2.5 Flash.
          Cache ID persisted in Firestore (config/context_cache). API contract unchanged:
          POST /search → { answer, facts: [{ fact, source_id, valid_at }] }.
          Citations returned as structured JSON via response_schema. Ingestion pipeline
          simplified to Steps 1–4 only (no chunking, no graph ingestion).
DEAD_ENDS: Graphiti (chosen in Sprint 1 spike): works, but over-engineered for this corpus
           size. Extraction quality problems observed (staff-name fixation, missing
           operational facts) would require significant prompt tuning that full-context
           retrieval avoids entirely.
           Pageindex (open-source): evaluated and rejected. The open-source version supports
           single-document discovery only — cross-document retrieval requires the commercial
           tier. This makes it unsuitable for a multi-document corpus where queries must
           span all sources. Not a workaround-able limitation; it is a product boundary.
