[2026-04-15]
CATEGORY: RETRIEVAL
SERVICE: poc/indexer
TASK: Priority 3 — navigational framing shift
SYMPTOM: Navigational framing ("which section would a reader turn to first?") produced
         identical recall to the baseline but drove precision from F1=0.68 to F1=0.34 on
         P1H. Average node count per query roughly tripled. P3H was unaffected.
ROOT_CAUSE: "Reader navigating" is a more permissive frame than "section likely to contain
         the answer" — the model interprets navigation as "anything useful to a thorough
         reader" rather than "what is strictly required". Under recall-oriented prompting,
         both framings include everything; navigational adds even more.
PREVENTED_BY: Before implementing a prompt reframe, verify the problem it is meant to
         solve actually exists in the current eval run — not just in a previous variant.
         P1H5 §1.13 was already selected by the recall-oriented baseline; the problem
         only manifested in fix2–fix5 (precision-tightened) prompts, which were reverted
         last session. Priority 3 was already solved by that revert.
SOLUTION: Reverted navigational framing. Baseline recall-oriented prompts restored.
DEAD_ENDS: Navigational framing ("A reader needs to answer this question — which sections
         would they turn to first?") — hurts precision without improving recall.
         "A reader working through this section — which subsections would they read?" —
         same effect at the discriminate stage.
